@node Installation
@chapter Installation

@cindex installing Dezyne

There are two ways te get started with Dezyne: use a binary installation
that we prepared especially for you, or you can build Dezyne from source
yourself.  When you plan on contributing to Dezyne (@pxref{Contributing}),
you may want to skip the sections on binary installation.

@menu
* Binary Installation::         Getting Dezyne running in no time!
* Requirements::                Software needed to build and run Dezyne.
@end menu

@node Binary Installation
@section Binary Installation

@cindex installing Dezyne, binary
This section describes how to install Dezyne on an arbitrary system from a
self-contained tarball providing binaries for Dezyne and for all its
dependencies.  This is often quicker than installing from source, which
is described in the next sections.  The only requirement is to have
GNU@tie{}tar and gzip.

@subsection Generic GNU/Linux Binary

Installing goes along these lines:

@enumerate
@item
@cindex binary installation
@cindex downloading Dezyne binary
@cindex GNU/Linux
Download the binary tarball from
@indicateurl{@value{BASE-URL}/dezyne-@value{VERSION}-x86_64-linux.tar.gz},
e.g.:

@example
$ wget @value{BASE-URL}/dezyne-@value{VERSION}-x86_64-linux.tar.gz
@end example

Make sure to download the associated @file{.sig} file and to verify the
authenticity of the tarball against it, do something like:

@example
$ wget @value{BASE-URL}/dezyne-@value{VERSION}-x86_64-linux.tar.gz.sig
$ gpg --verify dezyne-@value{VERSION}-x86_64-linux.tar.gz.sig
@end example

If that command fails because you do not have the required public key,
then run this command to import it:

@example
$ wget @value{OPENPGP-SIGNING-KEY-URL} \
      -qO - | gpg --import -
@end example

@noindent
and rerun the @code{gpg --verify} command.

Take note that a warning like ``This key is not certified with a trusted
signature!'' is normal.

Now, you can unpack the tarball; do something like:

@example
$ tar --warning=no-timestamp -xf /path/to/dezyne-@value{VERSION}-x86-64.tar.gz
@end example

Then try:
@example
$ cd dezyne-@value{VERSION}
$ ./dzn --help
@end example

@item
Make the @command{dzn} command available from other locations or to
other users on the machine, for instance with:

@example
$ ln -s $PWD/dzn ~/bin/dzn
or
# ln -s $PWD/dzn /usr/local/bin/dzn
@end example

@item
And optionally, make the @command{dzn-env}
prefix-command@footnote{@command{dzn-env} can be used as a prefix for
using programs from your operating system, such as @command{info},
@command{man}, or @command{emacs}; so that they may find and use the
documentation and extensions that are provided in the binary release.}
available:

@example
$ ln -s $PWD/dzn-env ~/bin/dzn-env
or
# ln -s $PWD/dzn-env /usr/local/bin/dzn-env
@end example

@c TODO: an installer script, either taking care of system-wide
@c installation (/usr/local, -- /opt?) or for an ordinary user: ~/bin/
@c or ~/.local/bin and environment settings?

@item
Test your installation

@example
$ dzn hello
$ dzn-env info dezyne
@end example

@end enumerate

@noindent
and get busy Dezyne'ing, @pxref{Getting Started}!  You can skip the
following sections about building from source.

@subsection Generic Microsoft Windows Binary

Installing goes along these lines:

@enumerate
@item
@cindex downloading Dezyne binary, Windows
@cindex binary installation, Windows
@cindex Windows
Download the binary zip archive from
@indicateurl{@value{BASE-URL}/dezyne-@value{VERSION}-x86_64-windows.zip},
@end enumerate

after which you can extract the archive by using 7zip
@url{https://www.7-zip.org/}.  Please do not use the built-in Windows
archive extraction tool: It does not honor the time stamps of the files
in the archive and thus produces a faulty installation.

If your system comes with a virus scanner, consider creating an
exception for dezyne-@value{VERSION}.

@dots{}

@noindent
and get busy Dezyne'ing, @pxref{Getting Started}!  You can skip the
following sections about building from source.

