@section Well-formedness Checks -- Nesting
The nesting of language constructs is restricted.  When we conceptually
'expand' @code{compound}s, two statement levels can be identified:

@itemize

@item The outer level we call @b{declarative}.  It consists of exactly
one @code{on}, optionally guarded at either side with
@code{guard}s and at most one @code{blocking}.  Valid examples
are:

@end itemize

@example
 1 on sensor.triggered(): @{ ...  @}
 2 [guard1] [guard2] on sensor.triggered(): @{ ...  @}
 3 [guard1] on sensor.triggered(): [guard2] @{ ...  @}
 4 on sensor.triggered(): [guard1] [guard2] @{ ...  @}
 5 [guard1] blocking [guard2] on sensor.triggered(): @{ ...  @}
 6 blocking [guard1] on sensor.triggered(): [guard2] @{ ...  @}
 7 on sensor.triggered(): [guard1] [guard2] blocking @{ ...  @}
@end example

@itemize

@item The inner level we call @b{imperative}.  It consists of @code{action}s
and @code{assign}s.  Imperative statements are only allowed within
a declarative context:

@end itemize

@example
 1 // the declarative part:
 2 [state.ARMED]
 3 @{
 4   on sensor.triggered():
 5   // the imperative part:
 6   @{
 7     console.detected();
 8     state = status.TRIGGERED;
 9   @}
10  @}
@end example

